				\begin{document}$${\mathrm{X}}0_{\mathrm{g}}^ +$$\end{document}X0g+ state. The resulting spectra contain only one R, one P, and sometimes one Q line, depending on the symmetry of the excited state. This capability greatly simplifies the analysis of the spectra, especially in cases where perturbations destroy the regularity of rotational levels in the upper state. When a bright state is perturbed by a dark state, the quantum mechanical mixing of these states causes their energies to shift, but also the strengths of related transitions to redistribute. Hence, the dark state becomes detectable for rotational levels where both states are sufficiently close in energy to perturb each other substantially.

